The much awaited automation of Aeronautical Information Service (AIS) is to be completed in December, this year. The AIS is a service established in support of international civil aviation, whose objective is to ensure the flow of information necessary for the safety, regularity, and efficiency of international air navigation. The managing director/CEO of the Nigerian Airspace Management Agency (NAMA), Capt. Fola Akinkuotu, who disclosed this in an interview at the weekend, said NAMA was putting a lot of pressures on the contractor to deliver the project in December. According to Akinkuotu, if not for COVID-19, the project ought to have been completed in August this year but the deadline has now been shifted to December this year. Capt Akinkuotu said: “As a matter of fact, we had a meeting with the contractors this week, though we meet with them regularly to let them know that this project must be completed as soon as possible. Because of covid-19, we shifted the commencement date to December, although the contractor said he wants more time but management has told them that, we cannot wait ad infinitum to complete the project”. Explaining that AIS project is one project he inherited, Akinkuotu added that, he had rammed it up since he joined NAMA and that the agency is making very good progress on the project. On efforts made so far, the NAMA boss informed that, the VSAT that was installed in Enugu was tweaked to be able to work. He however, pointed out, despite the fact that the project was not completed; NAMA used the opportunity of having the VSAT there to improve communication in that directive. “Overall, the project is going on fine. Our initial projection date was to complete it by August this year. Unfortunately, covid-19 came and it affected the manufacture of components outside because a lot of components are manufactured in Germany,” he stressed.  